Use case:

I'm currently working with nested objects:
```javascript
const someOtherArgs = { text: 'hey Lodash!', value: 42 }

const elements = [
  { type: 'something', ...someOtherArgs },
  {
    type: 'wrapper',
    children: [
      { type: 'somethingElse', ...someOtherArgs },
      {
        type: 'anotherWrapper',
        children: [
          { type: 'anItem' },
          { type: 'anotherItem' }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  { type: 'finally', ...someOtherArgs },
]
```

I need to have all my elements at the root level (I want to flatten the children of wrappers, recursively):
```javascript
const output = [
  { type: 'something', ...someOtherArgs },
  { type: 'somethingElse', ...someOtherArgs },
  { type: 'anItem' },
  { type: 'anotherItem' },
]
```

One ~~ugly~~ obvious method came to me:
```javascript
const output = _
    .chain(elements)
    .map(e => { return e.children || e })
    .flatMap()
    .map(e => { return e.children || e })
    .flatMap()
    // .filter({ type: 'somethingElse' }) // further computing...
    .value()
```
"Arrg! Code duplication!" (Yes, sorry for your eyes).
This duplication needs to be called as many times as there are nested levels.
I'm unwilling to let these lines stay in my code for more than a few seconds.
As I haven't found any functions (nor proposal) that would solve my problem, I imagined something like this:
```javascript
const out = _
  .chain(elements)
  .while(
    _.some(['children', _.isArray]), // predicate
    _.flow([ // function
      c => _.map(c, e => { return e.children || e }),
      _.flatMap
    ])
  )
  .value();
```
I know this solution isn't really a lightweight one.
It might not be the appropriate solution and I'm open to suggestions =)

Thanks for your time!

