Note (my current workaround):

I use a recursive function added as a mixin. This method avoids code duplication:
(function name isn't contractual)
```javascript
function flattenElements(elements = [], flattenBy = []) {
  return _
    .chain(elements)
    .map(e => {
      for (const index in flattenBy) {
        const key = flattenBy[index];
        if (e[key]) return flattenElements(e[key], flattenBy);
      }

      return e;
    })
    .flatMap()
    .value();
}

_.mixin({
  'flattenElements': flattenElements,
});

const output = _
  .chain(elements)
  .flattenElements(['children'])
  // .filter({ type: 'somethingElse' }) // further computing
  .value();
```

