I realise this sort of thing has [come](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/1413) [up](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/2872) [a lot](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/4064), but I think I've got a new take on how `_.merge` handles arrays. This all using v4.17.11.

Let's start with the example given for `_.merge` from the docs:
```js
var object = {
  'a': [{ 'b': 2 }, { 'd': 4 }]
};
 
var other = {
  'a': [{ 'c': 3 }, { 'e': 5 }]
};
 
_.merge(object, other);
// => { 'a': [{ 'b': 2, 'c': 3 }, { 'd': 4, 'e': 5 }] }
```

Here we can see that the two arrays at `a` are concatenated.

Now let's tweak the example:
```js
var object = {
  'a': [{ 'b': 2 }, { 'd': 4 }, { f: [6] }]
};
 
var other = {
  'a': [{ 'c': 3 }, { 'e': 5 }, { f: [7] }]
};
 
_.merge(object, other);
// => { a: [{ b: 2, c: 3 }, { d: 4, e: 5 }, { f: [7] }] }"
```

In this example, the two arrays at `a[2].f` are not concatenated.

Okay, so let's try simplifying that path a little:
```js
var object = {
  'a': [{ 'b': 2 }, { 'd': 4 }, [6]]
};
 
var other = {
  'a': [{ 'c': 3 }, { 'e': 5 }, [7]]
};
 
_.merge(object, other);
// => { a: [{ b: 2, c: 3 }, { d: 4, e: 5 }, [7]] }
```

In this case, the two arrays at `a[2]` are not concatenated.

Alright, so let's simplify the path a different way by getting rid of the 'outer' array:
```js
var object = {
  'a': { f: [6] }
};
 
var other = {
  'a': { f: [7] }
};
 
_.merge(object, other);
// => { a: { f: [7] } }
```

Once again, the two arrays at `a.f` are not concatenated.

-----

There's something not right here: `_.merge` should either always concatenate arrays, or never. Given that the docs state that "Array and plain object properties are merged recursively", I assume the intended behaviour is that the arrays in all of the above examples should have been concatenated.

Apologies if this has already been sorted for v5, but I couldn't find an issue that highlighted this behaviour this clearly.

