Somebody opened this issue in Jest's repo and I found a similar bug in Lodash too.
```
const a = {};
a.x = { x: a };

const b = {};
b.x = b;

lodash.isEqual(a, b) // true
lodash.isEqual(b, a) // false
```

The result value of `isEqual` is different if you switch the order of arguments. Other popular libraries have this bug too. Node's `isDeepStrictEqual` returns `false` in both cases.

